CAS Webinar - Special Topics in GLM

January 19, 2023

Special Topics in GLM

1 Introduction

We want to demonstrate several GLM techniques by building a claim frequency model using the French motor third-party liability dataset.

2 Descrption of the Dataset

In the freMTPL2freq dataset, risk features are collected for motor third-part liability policies (observed mostly on one year). In addition, we have claim numbers by policy(CASdatasets).The data dictionary is as follows.

  • IDpol The policy ID (used to link with the claims dataset).
  • ClaimNb Number of claims during the exposure period.
  • Exposure The period of exposure for a policy, in years.
  • VehPower The power of the car (ordered values).
  • VehAge The vehicle age, in years.
  • DrivAge The driver age, in years (in France, people can drive a car at 18).
  • BonusMalus Bonus/malus, between 50 and 350: <100 means bonus, >100 means malus in France.
  • VehBrand The car brand (unknown categories).
  • VehGas The car gas, Diesel or regular.
  • Area The density value of the city community where the car driver lives in: from “A” for rural area to “F” for urban centre.
  • Density The density of inhabitants (number of inhabitants per square-kilometer) of the city where the car driver lives in.
  • Region The policy region in France (based on the 1970-2015 classification).

3 Topic 1 The Theory Framework

The formula for multiple regression is defined as \(y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} +\beta_2 x_{i2}+...+\beta_p x_{ip}+ \varepsilon\) where i = 1, …, n(Number of rows). The objective function of multiple regression is the error term, \(\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} +\beta_2 x_{i2}+...+\beta_p x_{ip})^2\) Based on this analysis framework, a series of statistical tests such as \(R^2\) and F test are developed.

The formula for GLM is \(\ln(y_i) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} +\beta_2 x_{i2}+...+\beta_p x_{ip}\) Its objective function is to maximize \(\ln(\prod_{i=1}^{n}P(\mu_i = y_i))\) where we want to maximize the product of the likihood function. As such, the \(R^2\) and F test are not inherent statistical tests in the GLM framework.

4 Topic 2 Nonlinearity

For demonstration purpose, in this section we will use single variable, DrivAge in prediction. ## 4.1 Linear Fitting(underfit)

set.seed(1)
model = glm(ClaimNb ~ DrivAge, data=train, family= "poisson"(link='log'),weights=Exposure)
model

4.1.1 Goodness of Fit(Deviance residuals test)

cat("Deviance residuals test p-value: ",
1-pchisq(model$deviance, model$df.residual), end="\n")

4.1.2 Linear Fitting(Visualization)

chart = function(main){
  DrivAge_range = range(train$DrivAge)
DrivAge_grid = seq(from = DrivAge_range[1], to = DrivAge_range[2])
pred = predict(model, type = "response", newdata = list(DrivAge = DrivAge_grid ), se = TRUE)
table = train%>%group_by(DrivAge)%>%summarise(ex=sum(Exposure),cc=sum(ClaimNb))%>%mutate(fr=round((cc / ex), 3))
#balance factor
balance_fac = sum(table$fr)/sum(pred$fit)
par(mar = c(5, 4, 4, 4) + 0.3) 
h = (hist(train$DrivAge,breaks = nrow(table),col = "yellow",main = main, xlab = "Driver Age", ylab="Number of Policies"))
par(new=TRUE) 
plot(table$DrivAge,table$fr,bg ="purple",pch=21, axes = FALSE, xaxt="n",yaxt="n",xlab="",ylab="", ylim=c(0,0.3))
axis(side = 4, at = pretty(range(table$fr)))  
mtext("Claim Frequency", side = 4, line = 3) 
lines(DrivAge_grid, pred$fit*balance_fac, col = "darkgreen", lwd = 2)
lines(DrivAge_grid, pred$fit*balance_fac + 2*pred$se, lty = "dashed")
lines(DrivAge_grid, pred$fit*balance_fac - 2*pred$se, lty = "dashed")

}

chart("Linear Model")

set.seed(1)
model = glm(ClaimNb ~ ns(DrivAge,Boundary.knots = c(bk_1,bk_2), knots = c(k_1,k_2,k_3)), data=train, family= "poisson"(link='log'),weights=Exposure)

par(mar = c(5, 4, 4, 4) + 0.3)

mtext("Claim Frequency", side = 4, line = 3) 
lines(DrivAge_grid, pred$fit*balance_fac, col = "darkgreen", lwd = 2)
lines(DrivAge_grid, pred$fit*balance_fac + 2*pred$se, lty = "dashed")

5 Topic 3 Regularization and Variable Selection

5.1 Lasso Model

5.1.1 Lasso Concept

The objective function of Lasso is to maximize \(\ln(\prod_{i=1}^{n}P(\mu_i = y_i))-\lambda\sum_{i=1}^{p}|\beta_j|\), where we want to maximize this function to calculate \(\beta\)

5.1.2 Tuning Parameter Determination

splined = ns(train$DrivAge,Boundary.knots = c(bk_1,bk_2), knots = c(k_1,k_2,k_3))
splined_df = as.data.frame(splined)
X = cbind(train,splined_df)
X = X%>% select(-ClaimNb,-Exposure,-DrivAge)
X = model.matrix(~.-1,data = X )
set.seed(1)
cv.lasso =cv.glmnet(x = X, 
                    y = train$ClaimNb,
                    weights = train$Exposure,
                    family = "poisson",
                    alpha = 1,
                    nfolds=20)
cv.lasso$lambda.min

5.1.3 GLM using Lasso Model

mod_lasso = glmnet(x = X, y = train$ClaimNb,weights = train$Exposure, family= "poisson", alpha=1)
plot(mod_lasso,xvar="lambda",label=TRUE,lwd=2, main = "")
abline(v=log(cv.lasso$lambda.min),col='black',lty = 2,lwd=2)

5.1.4 Coefficients

coef.lasso = coef(mod_lasso,s=cv.lasso$lambda.min)
coef.lasso

5.2 Ridge Model

5.2.1 Ridge Concept

The objective function of Ridge is to maximize \(\ln(\prod_{i=1}^{n}P(\mu_i = y_i))-\lambda\sum_{i=1}^{p}\beta_j^2\), where we want to maximize this function to calculate \(\beta\) ## 5.2.2 GLM using Ridge

ridge = set.seed(1)
cv.ridge =cv.glmnet(x = X, 
                    y = train$ClaimNb,
                    weights = train$Exposure,
                    family = "poisson",
                    alpha = 0,
                    nfolds=20)

mod_ridge = glmnet(x = X, 
                    y = train$ClaimNb,
                    weights = train$Exposure,
                    family = "poisson",
                    alpha = 0)
coef.ridge = coef(mod_ridge,s=cv.ridge$lambda.min)
coef.ridge

5.3 Adaptive Lasso

5.3.1 Adaptive Lasso Concept

5.3.2 GLM using adaptive Lasso

gamma = 2
penalty.factor = 1/abs(coef.ridge[-1])^gamma
cv.adaptive_lasso = cv.glmnet(x = X, 
                    y = train$ClaimNb,
                    weights = train$Exposure,
                    family = "poisson",
                    #lasso
                    alpha = 1,
                    nfolds=20, 
                    penalty.factor = penalty.factor)
lambda = cv.adaptive_lasso$lambda.min
adaptive_lasso = glmnet(x = X, 
                    y = train$ClaimNb,
                    weights = train$Exposure,
                    family = "poisson",
                    #lasso
                    alpha = 1,
                    penalty.factor = penalty.factor)
plot(adaptive_lasso, xvar = "lambda", label = TRUE)
abline(v=log(lambda))

coef.adaptive_lasso = coef(adaptive_lasso,s=lambda)
coef.adaptive_lasso

5.4 Group LASSO

lambda = lambdamax(ClaimNb ~ .-Exposure - DrivAge +ns(DrivAge,Boundary.knots = c(bk_1,bk_2), knots = c(k_1,k_2,k_3)), data = train, penscale = sqrt, model = PoissReg())* 0.5^(0:5)
lambda = tail(lambda,1)
group_lasso <- grplasso(ClaimNb ~ .-Exposure - DrivAge +ns(DrivAge,Boundary.knots = c(bk_1,bk_2), knots = c(k_1,k_2,k_3)), data = train, model = PoissReg(), lambda = lambda)

coef.group_lasso = coef(group_lasso)
coef.group_lasso

options(scipen=999)
coef_compare = cbind.data.frame(matrix(coef.ridge), matrix(coef.lasso), matrix(coef.adaptive_lasso))

Prediction

splined = ns(test$DrivAge,Boundary.knots = c(bk_1,bk_2), knots = c(k_1,k_2,k_3))
splined_df = as.data.frame(splined)
test = test[,1:11]
newX = cbind(test,splined_df)
newX = newX%>% select(-ClaimNb,-Exposure,-DrivAge)
newX = model.matrix(~.-1,data = newX)
test$adaptive_lasso = predict(adaptive_lasso, newx = newX, s = lambda, type="response")
MSE = mean((test$adaptive_lasso-test$ClaimNb)^2)
cat("MSE of the adaptive lasso model is",MSE)

Gini Index

o <- with(test, order(adaptive_lasso))
x <- with(test, cumsum(Exposure[o])/sum(Exposure))
y <- with(test, cumsum(ClaimNb[o])/sum(ClaimNb))

dx <- x[-1] - x[-length(x)]
h <- (y[-1] + y[-length(y)])/2
gini <- 2 * (0.5 - sum(h * dx))

plot(x = x, y = y, type = "n")
lines(x = c(0,1), y = c(0,1), col = "grey")
lines(x = x, y = y, col = "red")
